; promontory’, <i>ros</i> ‘promontory, hill spur’). The Herefordshire and Wales placenames have the same meaning, derived from the Welsh elements which correspond to Middle Cornish <i>pen</i> + <i>ros</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William De Penrise was born about 1337 as the son of De Penrise. He had at least 1 daughter with Unknown."},"et":{"about 1337–":"umbes 1337–Surnud","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1379–Female":"1379–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1337":"1337","1379":"1379","1310":"1310","about 1337":"umbes 1337","about 1379":"umbes 1379"},"fi":{"about 1337–":"noin 1337–Kuollut","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1379–Female":"1379–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1379":"1379","1310":"1310","about 1337":"noin 1337","about 1379":"noin 1379"},"fr":{"about 1337–":"environ 1337–Décédé","1337–Male":"1337–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1379–Female":"1379–Décédée","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1337":"1337","1379":"1379","1310":"1310","about 1337":"environ 1337","about 1379":"environ 1379","lifeSummary":"William De Penrise est né environ 1337, fils de De Penrise. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Unknown."},"de":{"about 1337–":"um 1337–Verstorben","1337–Male":"1